postcontent: Second Model BIn 1931, production shifted entirely to this updated version which added several, mostly external,features to make the pistol look and handle more like the Colt 1911A1. The frame was changed to provide an arched backstrap and a larger safety as well as more rugged and higher-visibility sights were fitted. Numerous small changes were implemented across the design, from a shortening of the barrel bushing, to elimination of the separate safety guide bar.Large numbers of these guns were produced. The image at the top of the page is a typical european commercial model with wood stocks and blue finish. Many variations of finish, stocks and sights were produced. This basic model B remained in production continuously until 1983.

title: For Sale:  USED P64 9X18 MAK. GOOD PLUS CONDITION
postcontent: The P-64 is a blowback operated, double-action pistol. Although designed from scratch by Polish engineers, the P-64 is very similar to German Walther PPK and is sometimes described erroneous in western literature as it's clone. Frame and slide are made of steel and the finish is blue. The barrel is fixed to the frame with the recoil spring wound around it. The controls consist of a slide mounted safety lever and a magazine catch. The safety lever has two positions: up for "fire" and down for "safe" and decocks the hammer (if cocked) when put on safe. The safety mechanism allows the slide to be operated with safety on. Unlike the Walther, the P-64's magazine release is located at the bottom of the frame, slowing down the reloading process. The single-column magazines hold 6 rounds. The slides locks back when the last round from the magazine is fired but there is no external slide release. Double-action trigger pull is heavy: 110-120 N (25-27 lb). The sights are fixed and set at a rather exaggerated distance of 50 meters. A loaded-chamber indicator is located in the rear part of the slide, just above the hammer. Grips are checkered black plastic.

Built on the famous Serbian AK M70 Imported kits, the M70B1 features sexy all black polymer furniture and heavy duty build.  They are easy to spot with the bulged front trunion for added strength. Brand new USA made receiver and barrel with a beautifully hard finish, not the normal crappy bluing.

This AK-47 M70B1 PAP 7.62x39mm rifle features a 16" barrel, black poly stock set with black synthetic pistol grip, Yugo pattern RPK heavy duty receiver, combination grenade launching sights/gas cut-off valve, a slant cut muzzle brake, and bayonet lug.  Also includes the original (rare!) grenade launching muzzle attachment with the repro rifle grenade, the cleaning kit, and a tactical soft case.  Comes with 2 30-round hi capacity magazines.  The kits were manufactured in Serbia in the famous Zastava Military Arms factory and sent to the US for builds into complete 922R legal rifles. Accepts all standard in spec AK magazines for 7.62x39 caliber. 

I fired one magazine through this, although you'd never know it because it looks better than most new AK's on the store shelves - the safety/selector lever has barely started to wear the arc into the finish.  I've never used the grenade launcher muzzle attachment or the grenade.  The trigger and action are awesome, easily the slickest and best I've ever felt on a stock AK.  This very rare package can be yours for less than most people are asking for their used WASR's on Armslist.  Impress your friends and scare the he** out of your neighbors at the same time!  I'm not going to be sad if this doesn't sell (at least I can tell my wife "I tried") so no trades or lower cash offers at this time.

I can add ammo for extra cash, but it don't have any blanks to launch the grenade.  I can also add a brand new 75-round drum or 40-round mag for extra ($75 and $20 respectively).

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1895 Krag
postcontent: This Springfield Armory Model 1895 .30/40 Krag-Jorgensen rifle finish has faded to a plum brown to a dull pewter gray patina, mixing with light freckling, but nothing out of the ordinary for its age and commensurate usage. No cracks or repairs. Metal surfaces are free of rust or corrosion. The action is tight and works perfectly. The walnut stock and handguard are in very good condition and have small handling marks and minor blemishes in the original oil finish, as well as a crisp cartouche on the left side of the wrist. The top of the receiver is clearly marked MODEL 1895 SPRINGFIELD ARMORY. It has a 30" barrel, a side loading 5 round box magazine, a long range folding ladder rear sight. According to the serial number this is the lot right before the rifles were given to Teddy Roosevelt's Rough Riders in the Spanish American War. The Springfield Model 1892-99 Krag-Jorgensen rifle is a Norwegian-design bolt action rifle that was adopted in 1892 as the standard United States Army military longarm, chambered in U.S. caliber .30-40 Krag. All versions and variants were manufactured under license by the Springfield Armory between 1892 and 1903. The U.S. Krag was replaced beginning in 1903 with the introduction of the M1903 Springfield rifle. A piece of history for the Military Collector. Shoots well. Time for me to pass it on.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom 1911 Government .45 ACP
postcontent:
Base gun is a Norinco 1911A1. These make for great base guns due to the steel used to forge the frame and slide. More specifically, they use railroad steel, which is extremely hard and durable, so much so that gunsmiths abhor it because it ruins their tool sets. However, the benefits of it for a firearm are obvious. Gun was customized by a certified gunsmith. It started out as a basic GI configured gun, and was customized as seen here. I picked up years ago, and after using it in a few competition matches, stuck it in the safe where it has sat. I got in a trade, already used. I will not lie, the gun is used, and it reflects use, which is why I am asking for a fairly low price. However, please not that it was not abused, just used. The previous owner allowed a patina to take hold of the slide, and its one hell of a patina. If you don't like it, you can get it refinished. I do not know the parts list, but in addition to obvious after market parts, the gun has been very finely polished on the inside. It is very smooth, and the trigger has been so fine tuned that it is one of the best I've come across. Gun is very reliable and durable. It'll outlast you and run all day long. It just isn't pretty anymore. If you're looking for an old 1911 to make a project out of, or want a beater that'll run, here you go. If a project is your fancy, I'd suggest you don't screw with the action and trigger, but it's up to you. Comes with one old Ed Brown 8 round magazine and zippered soft case.
